New legal powers mean the worst offenders now face fines of up to £500,000, but despite thousands of complaints to the ICO, the BBC programme revealed there had not been any fines imposed on offending companies for at least 18 months.

Information Commissioner Christopher Graham said: 'Last year we gained tough new powers to tackle unsolicited marketing calls and texts. We are working to identify the operators responsible.

'The ICO has executed search warrants at a number of sites across the UK linked to companies we believe are breaking the law.

'We have also set up an online reporting mechanism on our website that allows people to report any marketing texts or calls from unidentified senders.'

An exact total of 7,095 complaints were received under the Privacy and Electronic Communication Regulations (PECR), which govern electronic marketing, last year, up from 4,953 in 2010/11, the ICO's annual report showed.

